benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: PUT /1.0/kb/invoiceItems/{invoiceItemId}/customFields - Modify custom fields to invoice item

covered: Valid PUT request flows with different header scenarios (TC01–TC05, TC12, TC21–TC22).
Non-existent resource handling and state variations covered (TC07, TC24–TC25).
Comprehensive error handling for bad requests (TC06, TC08–TC11), missing/invalid authentication (TC09, TC13), and malformed payloads (TC08, TC14).
Handling of server/service failures and timeouts (TC15–TC19) including 500/503/504 responses and related messages.
Data integrity and idempotency considerations addressed (TC17, TC18), plus performance tests (TC20–TC21).
Edge cases covered (TC22 minimum values, TC23 extra URL params).
gaps: Partial update behavior is not explicitly tested to verify rejection or handling of partial payloads for PUT.
No tests addressing concurrency/race conditions when multiple clients update the same invoice item simultaneously.
Authorization depth limited to authentication failure (401); no explicit 403 forbidden scenarios for insufficient permissions.
No rate limiting/throttling tests (e.g., 429) and no caching behavior tests (ETag/Cache-Control).
Pagination considerations are not relevant for single-resource PUT, but no explicit validation of large pagination-related metadata where applicable.
No explicit tests validating exact error payload structure across all error scenarios (beyond generic messages).
recommendations: Add a concurrency/race condition test to ensure consistency when multiple clients update the same invoice item simultaneously (e.g., with versioning or locking).
Introduce 403 forbidden scenarios to verify proper handling when authentication is valid but permissions are insufficient.
Add rate limiting tests (e.g., 429) and examine system behavior under throttling conditions.
Add caching tests to validate ETag/If-None-Match headers and cache invalidation on updates.
Incorporate explicit tests for partial payloads to confirm whether partial updates are rejected or accepted per API spec, and ensure consistent behavior with PUT semantics.
